07749nam a22010695i 9783110588255DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20182018gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831105882557 a10.1515/97831105882552doi  a(DE-B1597)491259  a(OCoLC)1046610689  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aB839b.S57 2018 7aPHI0220002bisacsh04a149.9122300aSo What's New About Scholasticism? :bHow Neo-Thomism Helped Shape the Twentieth Century /ced. by Rajesh Heynickx, Stéphane Symons. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (X, 309 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tTable of Contents -- tInto Neo-Thomism: Reading the Fabric of an Intellectual Movement -- tPart I .Shaping A New Society -- tThe Thomist Debate over Inequality and Property Rights in Depression-Era Europe -- tReligion, human rights and democracy in post-1940 France in theory and practice: from Maritain’s Thomism to Vignaux’s secular realism -- tEpistemological Tracks: On Religion, Words, and Buildings in 1950’s Belgium -- tWhen Personalism Met Planning: Jacques Maritain and a British Christian Intellectual Circle, 1937–1949 -- tPart II. Encountering Phenomenology, Existentialism, and Aesthetics -- tNeo-Scholasticism, Phenomenology, and the Problem of Conversion -- tA Great Deal of Controversy? A Case Study of Dondeyne, Grégoire, and Moeller Integrating Phenomenology and Existentialism in Louvain Neo-Thomism -- tGilson’s Poietics -- tPart III. Reconciling Science and Religion -- tPsychology from a Neo-Thomist Perspective. The Louvain-Madrid Connection -- tScience contra Science. The Battle for Legitimate Knowledge in the Spanish Catholic Journals in the Early Twentieth Century -- tPart IV. Mediating Tradition -- tThe Analogy of Marshall McLuhan -- tVetera Novis Augere: Neo-Scholastic Philosophers and Their Concepts of Tradition -- tThomas Aquinas or John Henry Newman? The Intellectual Itinerary of Johannes Willebrands -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex of Persons0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn So What’s New about Scholasticism? thirteen international scholars gauge the extraordinary impact of a religiously inspired conceptual framework in a modern society. The essays that are brought together in this volume reveal that Neo-Thomism became part of contingent social contexts and varying intellectual domains. Rather than an ecclesiastic project of like-minded believers, Neo-Thomism was put into place as a source of inspiration for various concepts of modernization and progress. This volume reconstructs how Neo-Thomism sought to resolve disparities, annul contradictions and reconcile incongruent, new developments. It asks the question why Neo-Thomist ideas and arguments were put into play and how they were transferred across various scientific disciplines and artistic media, growing into one of the most influential master-narratives of the twentieth century. Edward Baring, Dries Bosschaert, James Chappel, Adi Efal-Lautenschläger, Rajesh Heynickx, Sigrid Leyssen, Christopher Morrissey, Annette Mülberger, Jaume Navarro, Herman Paul, Karim Schelkens, Wim Weymans and John Carter Wood reconstruct a bewildering, yet decipherable thought-structure that has left a deep mark on twentieth century politics, philosophy, science and religion.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aNeo-Scholasticism. 4aNeuscholastik. 4aNouvelle Théologie. 4aThomas von Aquin. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh  aNeo-Scholasticism.  aNew Theology.  aThomas Aquinas.1 aBaring, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBosschaert, Dries, econtributor.4c